<p>Making waves in the underground London art scene, we sat down with Jaffar to discuss everything from how he got started in art, to his upcoming “Black Angst” exhibition &#8211;&nbsp; a show that delves into the murky waters felt by black people asked to assimilate into a system that cannot compute ones existence.</p>



<div class="wp-block-columns collapse-above-right">
<div class="wp-block-column">
<p><strong>Have you always wanted to be an artist?</strong></p>



<p>I don’t recall stumbling across peers like myself in my early years of education that actually wanted to be an artist or even spoken openly about always wanting to be an artist. Our school was filled with children of the diaspora or had parents from the diaspora. So, you can already imagine how we are conditioned at home to strive for “economically stable” jobs that allow us the “coloured”, “Other” individual to be accepted in our journey of assimilation in this Babylon.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Same goes for the state schools we went to. Everyone in that school is just trying to pump you out, and that is it. But there are always those teachers who do add an element of care. And it did spark a level of want for art. But at the end you are funnelled through the hole they want you exiting. I only felt comfortable being an artist when I started to see others like myself.&nbsp; And that was only near the end of my undergrad in Anthropology.</p>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img width="679" height="1024" src="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar13-679x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-3754" srcset="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar13-679x1024.jpg 679w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar13-768x1159.jpg 768w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar13-1018x1536.jpg 1018w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar13-1320x1992.jpg 1320w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar13.jpg 1358w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></figure>
</div>
</div>



<p>So, thank you to those who looked like me and spearheaded a route for myself to follow behind.</p>



<div class="wp-block-columns" id="collapse-below-left">
<div class="wp-block-column">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="679" height="1024" src="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar8-679x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-3758" srcset="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar8-679x1024.jpg 679w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar8-768x1158.jpg 768w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar8-1019x1536.jpg 1019w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar8-1320x1990.jpg 1320w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar8.jpg 1359w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></figure>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column">
<p><strong>What influences your work? Who do you look up to as an artist?</strong></p>



<p>I don’t get mad when people assume I get my influence from Basquiat. Who hasn’t he influenced? He literally flipped the art world on its head. But what influences me are the fellow artist around me. They’re real to me, they are near me and have affected me personally. There are many to thank,&nbsp;anti.net, my muse Katherine Duke, my family, and my friends. I look up to all of them, truly. They all add different elements to my creation. From the frustration and the joy, they make me feel, they fuel the emotive brushstrokes I’m used to producing.&nbsp;</p>



<p><strong>Who would you love to collab with?</strong></p>



<p>Right now, I want to collab with as many local artists. Let us do a piece together and get it exhibited and make versions for the peopledem to have hung in their yard.</p>
</div>
</div>



<p>I guess for the future. I’d love to work with fashion companies and just do my work over their visions. I’d love to eventually though work closely with exhibition and build my own version. Nah scrap that, I want to build an exhibition that will blow the Tate and White Cube out of the waters man. And what will make it better is that it will be accessible to people. Accessibility right now in the art world is a myth.&nbsp;</p>



<div class="wp-block-columns collapse-above-right">
<div class="wp-block-column">
<p><strong>What do you have coming up next?</strong></p>



<p>Right now, I’ve got my exhibition titled ‘Black Angst’ coming up from the 28<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;of June and ends on the 4<sup>th</sup>&nbsp;of July at the No Format Gallery. It’s a series that’s been two years in the making and it finally out there for display. Black Angst is just delving into an artist&#8217;s approach on angst, specifically Black Angst. With ambiguity and precarity in this Black mind, angst begins to build, which leads to emotions of fear, frustration, and despair.</p>



<p>Each of the art pieces presented in this gallery will be a snapshot of my Black emotions. After ‘Black Angst’, me and my boy Bradley Banton have a show at the Bermondsey Project Space titled ‘What Changes if I Change?’. An exhibition that delves into the murky waters of assimilating to a system that cannot compute your existence. It’ll be a special show as Bradley will be screening his film ‘Blackmael’ &nbsp;and fam, it’s a mad one.&nbsp;</p>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="679" height="1024" src="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar3-1-679x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-3805" srcset="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar3-1-679x1024.jpg 679w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar3-1-768x1159.jpg 768w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar3-1-1018x1536.jpg 1018w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar3-1-1320x1992.jpg 1320w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/jaffar3-1.jpg 1358w" sizes="(max-width: 679px) 100vw, 679px" /></figure>
</div>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-columns" id="collapse-above-left">
<div class="wp-block-column">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="1024" src="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/black-angst-poster-1024x1024.jpg" alt="" class="wp-image-3793" srcset="./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/black-angst-poster-1024x1024.jpg 1024w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/black-angst-poster-768x768.jpg 768w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/black-angst-poster-1536x1536.jpg 1536w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/black-angst-poster-200x200.jpg 200w, ./../../../wp-content/uploads/2021/06/black-angst-poster-1320x1320.jpg 1320w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</div>



<div class="wp-block-column">
<p><strong>What would be a dream venue for you to exhibit your work (anywhere, any country) ?</strong></p>



<p>Personally, I’d be happy if it even gets into any blue-chip galleries. As long as my work is racking up value and I manage to finesse the bag. I am happy. But I guess everyone would want to exhibit their work in the Tate, White Cube, Serpentine, 180 Strand. All the big names. Now if I managed to get into these spaces, you don’t understand the waves I’ll be making for my peopledem. It’ll be mad!</p>
</div>
